{{-plasia}} '''Aplasia''' ({{IPAc-en|ə|ˈ|p|l|eɪ|ʒ|ə|audio=En-us-aplasia.ogg}}; from [[Greek language|Greek]] ''a'' (not, no); ''plasis'' (molding)) is defined in general as "defective development or congenital absence of an [[organ (anatomy)|organ]] or [[Tissue (biology)|tissue]]."<ref name=Stedman>{{Cite book | title = Stedman's medical dictionary | date = 1990 | publisher = Williams and Wilkins | location = Baltimore | isbn = 0-683-07916-6 | pages = 106}}</ref><ref name=DrugsDotCom>{{cite web |url=https://www.drugs.com/dict/aplasia.html |title= Stedman's > aplasia |publisher=Drugs.com |accessdate=17 February 2010}}</ref> In the field of [[hematology]], the term refers to "incomplete, retarded, or defective development, or cessation of the usual regenerative process."<ref name=Stedman/><ref name=DrugsDotCom/>
==Examples== *[[Acquired pure red cell aplasia]] *[[Aplasia cutis congenita]] *[[Aplastic anemia]] *Germ cell aplasia, also known as [[Sertoli cell-only syndrome]] *[[Radial aplasia]] *[[Thymus|Thymic]] aplasia, which is found in [[DiGeorge syndrome]] and also occurs naturally as part of the gradual loss of function of the [[immune system]] later in life
== See also == * [[Atrophy]] * [[Hyperplasia]] * [[Hypoplasia]] * [[Neoplasia]] * [[List of biological development disorders]]
