{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}} {{Use British English|date=February 2013}} {{Italic title}} {{Infobox book <!-- |italic title = (see above) --> | name = ''Freaks, Geeks, and Asperger Syndrome: A User Guide to Adolescence'' | image = Freaks, Geeks, and Asperger Syndrome.jpg <!-- include the file, px and alt: [[File:Example.jpg|200px|alt=Cover]] --> | caption = | author = [[Luke Jackson (author)|Luke Jackson]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = England | language = English | series = | subject = Asperger Syndrome | genre = Non-fiction | publisher = Jessica Kingsley Publishers | pub_date = 15 August 2002 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Paperback | pages = 224 | isbn = 978-1-84310-098-0 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = Crystalline Lifetime: Fragments of Asperger Syndrome }} '''''Freaks, Geeks, and Asperger Syndrome: A User Guide to Adolescence''''' is a non-fiction book about how it is like having [[Asperger Syndrome]]. The book was written by the then 13-year-old [[Luke Jackson (author)|Luke Jackson]] who has Asperger Syndrome himself. Luke wrote the book because he thought that there were not enough useful things on the internet about the subject.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/4614001.stm |title=Bilingual book tackles Asperger's |date=6 June 2005 |work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref>
The point of the book is to explain that it is fine to be different. Luke goes through the problems that people with Asperger Syndrome face such as trouble reading facial expressions and body language. Luke Jackson lives in a family with three brothers and three sisters and his siblings have related difficulties as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ps.psychiatryonline.org/article.aspx?articleID=89362 |title=Book Reviews: Personal Accounts: Asperger Syndrome |author=Kamlyn Haynes, Jeffrey Geller |date=1 November 2004 |work=Psychiatric Services}}</ref>
==Reception== David Worling of the Canadian Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry said that the book is filled with valuable information and is useful to have in a clinical library.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Freaks, Geeks, & Asperger Syndrome: A User Guide to Adolescence |author=David Worling |year=2005 |work= Canadian Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry |pmc=2542912 |page=85 |volume=14 |issue=3}}</ref>
The book received first place in [[Times Educational Supplement]] awards in 2003 for special educational needs books.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tes.co.uk/article.aspx?storycode=385803 |title=Everyone is good at something |author=Geraldine Brennan |date=24 October 2003 |work=[[TES-Newspaper]]}}</ref>
