'''Jolan Chang''' (9 December 1917 - 25 April 2002) was a [[Chinese people|Chinese]]-[[Canadians|Canadian]] [[Sexology|sexologist]] and [[Taoism|Taoist]] [[philosopher]] who wrote the luminary classics on Eastern Sexuality ''The Tao of Love and Sex'' and ''The Tao of the Loving Couple''. He was born in [[Hangzhou]] as the son of an army general. After the revolution he lived for a number of years in Canada, but later he moved to [[Sweden]]. He died in [[Stockholm]].

British author [[Lawrence Durrell]] wrote about Chang in his 1980 book ''A smile in the Mind's Eye.''

''The Tao of Love and Sex'' (with foreword and postscript by [[Joseph Needham]]) interprets ancient [[Taoist sexual practices|Taoist sexual teachings]] into a modern model of [[Human sexuality|sexuality]]. Beginning with a background of [[Tao]] and [[Yin and yang|yin/yang]], the book then goes into the following subjects: the role of women in sex, the importance of sexuality to [[health]], [[ejaculation]] control, [[hip thrusting|thrusting]] methods, descriptions of various [[sex position]]s, advantages of [[Woman on top (sex position)|female superior positions]], erotic [[kiss]]ing and the Tao, overcoming [[impotence]], the importance of female satisfaction, [[longevity]] in relation to sexual health, benefits of [[Age disparity in sexual relationships|age differences between sexual partners]] and [[breathing]] exercises. The book demonstrated that the principles of ancient Taoist texts are applicable to stimulating and improving sexual health today.

== Works ==

