'''Muesli belt malnutrition''' is a term coined by Professor Vincent Marks,<ref name="Straten1997">{{cite book | author = Michael Van Straten | title = Healing Foods: Nutrition for the Mind, Body and Spirit | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Jy_I2QAMpd8C | date = 1 January 1997 | publisher = Welcome Rain | isbn = 978-1-55670-662-2 | quote = Professor Vincent Marks at the University of Surrey coined the phrase "muesli-belt malnutrition," an accurate description of this over-zealous attitude. Serious ... }}</ref><ref name="Cannon1988">{{cite book | author = Geoffrey Cannon | title = The Politics of Food | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=oFJEAAAAYAAJ | year = 1988 | publisher = Century | isbn = 978-0-7126-1717-8 | pages = 124– | quote = They are the forgotten children, victims of health-foodism, sufferers from muesli belt malnutrition. But now they have a saviour. The courageous Professor Vincent Marks .... There is now every chance that the neglected children of food faddism ... }}</ref> author of the book ''[[Panic Nation]]'',<ref>{{cite book | last = LeMesurier | first = Peter | title = The New Age Lexicon | publisher = 0 Books | date = 2005 | location = Hants, UK | pages = 87 | isbn = 1-903816-98-X }}</ref> to describe the supposed phenomenon that parents feeding their children what is seen as an "extremely healthy" diet could be depriving their children of essential fats.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/muesli-belt-kids-face-the-threat-of-starvation-1160104.html | title = Muesli-belt kids face the threat of starvation | date = 9 May 1998 | work = The Independent | accessdate = 12 July 2016 }}</ref><ref name="Webb2012">{{cite book | author = Geoffrey P. Webb | title = Nutrition: Maintaining and improving health, Fourth edition | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9inOBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA463 | date = 31 August 2012 | publisher = CRC Press | isbn = 978-1-4441-4247-1 | pages = 463– }}</ref><ref name="MorganDickerson2003">{{cite book | author1 = Jane B. Morgan | author2 = John W. T. Dickerson | title = Nutrition in Early Life | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=d7AQn2Ol6gUC&pg=PA245 | date = 4 April 2003 | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | isbn = 978-0-470-85792-2 | pages = 245– }}</ref>
A study carried out at [[Bristol University]] examining the diets of British toddlers found that such fears were overstated. The study found that while children in the lowest fat group had lower intakes of [[zinc]] and [[vitamin A]], children in the highest fat group ingested less [[iron]] and [[vitamin C]]. Overall the children were not seriously deprived of any essential nutrients, regardless of their diets.<ref>{{cite press release | title = No evidence of 'muesli-belt malnutrition' in British Toddlers | publisher = Bristol University | date = 2002-03-12 | url = http://www.bris.ac.uk/news/2002/alspaclowfat.htm | accessdate = 2008-04-03 }}</ref>
