{{technical|date=September 2015}}
{{Infobox medical condition | name = {{PAGENAME}} | synonyms = | image = | alt = | caption = | pronounce = | field = | ICD10 = K83.0 | ICD9 = <!--{{ICD9|xxx}}--> | ICDO = | OMIM = | DiseasesDB = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicineSubj = | eMedicineTopic = | MeSH = | GeneReviewsNBK = | GeneReviewsName = | Orphanet = 447774 }} '''Secondary sclerosing cholangitis''' (SSC) is a [[Chronic condition|chronic]] cholestatic liver disease. It is an aggressive and rare disease with complex and multiple causes. It is characterized by inflammation, fibrosis, destruction of the biliary tree and biliary cirrhosis. It can be treated with minor interventions, antibiotics, and monitoring, or with more serious cases, surgery, endoscopic intervention, and liver transplantation.
==Cause== SSC is thought to develop as a consequence of known injuries or pathological processes of the biliary tree, such as biliary obstruction, surgical trauma to the bile duct, or ischemic injury to the biliary tree. Secondary causes of SSC include [[Gallstone|intraductal stone disease]], [[surgical]] or [[blunt trauma|blunt]] [[abdominal trauma]], intra-[[arterial]] [[chemotherapy]], and recurrent [[pancreatitis]].<ref name="pmid17058222">{{cite journal |vauthors=Abdalian R, Heathcote EJ |title=Sclerosing cholangitis: a focus on secondary causes |journal=[[Hepatology (journal)|Hepatology]] |volume=44 |issue=5 |pages=1063–74 |date=November 2006 |pmid=17058222 |doi=10.1002/hep.21405 |issn=}}</ref> It has been clearly demonstrated sclerosing cholangitis can develop after an episode of severe bacterial [[cholangitis]].<ref name="pmid12057011">{{cite journal |vauthors=ter Borg PC, van Buuren HR, Depla AC | title = Bacterial cholangitis causing secondary sclerosing cholangitis: a case report | journal = BMC Gastroenterology | volume = 2| pages = 14 |date=June 2002 | pmid = 12057011 | pmc = 116430 | doi = 10.1186/1471-230X-2-14| url = | issn = }}</ref> Also it was suggested that it can result from insult to the biliary tree by obstructive cholangitis secondary to [[choledocholithiasis]], surgical damage, trauma, vascular insults, [[parasitism|parasites]], or congenital fibrocystic disorders. Additional causes of secondary SC are toxic, due to chemical agents or drugs.<ref name="pmid12516911">{{cite journal |vauthors=Kariv R, Konikoff FM | title = Sclerosing cholangitis--primary, secondary and more.. | journal = The Israel Medical Association Journal : IMAJ | volume = 4 | issue = 12 | pages = 1141–2 |date=December 2002 | pmid = 12516911 | doi = | url = | issn = }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Secondary sclerosing cholangitis|url=http://www.nature.com/nrgastro/journal/v6/n5/full/nrgastro.2009.46.html|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref>
==Diagnosis== The [[diagnosis]] of SSC requires the [[Diagnosis of exclusion|exclusion]] of secondary causes of [[sclerosing cholangitis]] and recognition of associated conditions that may potentially imitate its classic cholangiographic features. It is morphologically similar to [[primary sclerosing cholangitis]] ([[primary sclerosing cholangitis|PSC]]) but originates from a known [[pathology|pathological process]]. Its [[Illness|clinical]] and [[cholangiography|cholangiographic]] features may mimic PSC, yet its natural history may be more favorable if recognition is prompt and appropriate therapy is introduced. Sclerosing cholangitis in critically ill patients, however, is associated with rapid disease progression and poor outcome.<ref>{{cite web|title=Causes of Secondary Sclerosing Cholangitis|url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/761739_8|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> Serologic testing, radiological imaging and histological analysis can help diagnose SSC.<ref>{{cite web|title=Secondary Sclerosing Cholangitis due to Gallbladder Adenocarcinoma|url=http://www.karger.com/Article/Fulltext/345961|accessdate=6 January 2017}}</ref> ==Treatment== {{Empty section|date=November 2017}}
